    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug read-peripheral DBGMCU",
        "description": "Read DBGMCU peripheral on L476RG probe"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Multiple ST-LINK probes are attached, so I need to pick one explicitly:\nThe project targets the NUCLEO-L476RG, so I'll pin its probe:\nNo \u2014 the debug port itself is not disabled. The fact that the recipe attached over SWD and read DBGMCU at all proves the DAP is alive (and the descriptor's L476RG probe was used; IDCODE confirms it: DEV_ID `0x415` = STM32L4x6, REV_ID `0x1007`).\n\nHere's the decoded **DBGMCU** state (base `0xE0042000`):\n\n| Register | Value | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| `CR` | `0x00000000` | **DBG_SLEEP=0, DBG_STOP=0, DBG_STANDBY=0**, TRACE_IOEN=0 |\n| `APB1_FZR1/2`, `APB2_FZR` | `0x0` | No timer/watchdog freeze-on-halt bits set |\n\nInterpretation:\n\n- **Nothing in software has disabled debug** \u2014 there's no \"debug off\" bit in DBGMCU on the L4; the port is hardware-on unless RDP level 2 locks it out, which clearly isn't the case since we just connected.\n- **But debug is not kept alive in low-power modes.** With `DBG_SLEEP/DBG_STOP/DBG_STANDBY` all 0 (the reset default), the debug clocks stop when the core enters Sleep/Stop/Standby. If your symptom is \"the debugger loses the target / can't halt it after a while,\" this is the classic cause: firmware never called `HAL_DBGMCU_EnableDBGStopMode()` (or set the bits directly), so any low-power entry severs the connection.\n- TRACE_IOEN=0 just means SWO/trace pins aren't enabled \u2014 unrelated to the SWD port.\n\nSo: if your firmware uses `__WFI()`/Stop mode, set `DBGMCU->CR |= DBG_SLEEP | DBG_STOP` (or the HAL equivalents) in a debug build to keep the port reachable. Otherwise the debug port is fully functional as-is."
}